<HEADLINE>
FORMER NATIONAL PALACE MUSEUM CURATOR DIES OF HEART ATTACK
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Taipei,  Jan. 6 (CNA) 01/06/07  13:40:37 (By Sofia Wu)
</P>
<P>
Former National Palace Museum curator Chin Hsiao-yi died of a
heart attack Friday at the age of 87, his family said Saturday.
</P>
<P>
Chin, born in Hunan Province in central China, was one of the
most trusted confidants of the late President Chiang Kai-shek. He
traveled to the United States to pursue advanced study at the
University of Oklahoma after graduating from a commerce and legal
college in Shanghai.
</P>
<P>
He was recruited by Chiang to work at the Kuomintang's (KMT's)
headquarters in Nanjing at a tender age of 24. After the KMT
government  moved  its seat to Taiwan,  Chin became  Chiang's
confidential secretary for many years.
</P>
<P>
Fluent in writing, Chin was one of Chiang's key speech writers.
Chiang's will was also drafted by Chin.
</P>
<P>
Following Chiang's death in 1975, Chin served as the KMT's deputy
secretary- general. In 1983, he became curator of the National
Palace Museum in suburban Taipei, home to the best of ancient
Chinese art treasures. He retired from the post in 2000.
</P>
